orgere -- tInformed consent - citizens0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHealth programmes that offer »help to self-help« are meant to empower ageing adults to remain independent and self-sufficient at home for as long as possible. But what happens when the private home becomes a political realm in which state intervention and individual agency happen simultaneously? Based on 15 months of ethnographic fieldwork in a Danish municipality, Amy Clotworthy describes how both health professionals and elderly citizens negotiate the political discourses about health and ageing that frame their relational encounter. By elucidating some of the conflicts, paradoxes, and negotiations that occur, she provides important insights into the contemporary organisation of eldercare.  afunded by des Center for Healthy Aging at the University of Copenhagen  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aAging Studies. 4aBody. 4aCare. 4aCultural Studies. 4aDenmark. 4aEldercare. 4aHealth Initiatives. 4aMedicine. 4aQualitative Social Research. 4aReablement. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh  aAging Studies.  aBody.  aCare.  aCultural Studies.  aDenmark.  aEldercare.  aHealth Initiatives.  aMedicine.  aQualitative Social Research.  aReablement.2 ades Center for Healthy Aging at the University of Copenhagenefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020